WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.320 --> 00:00:03.645
Today we're going to talk
about Ireland and England,

00:00:03.645 --> 00:00:07.515
predominantly England not
because Ireland isn't important,

00:00:07.515 --> 00:00:11.340
but because we know
less about Ireland.

00:00:11.340 --> 00:00:14.205
The reason we know relatively

00:00:14.205 --> 00:00:17.355
more about England in
its Post Roman period,

00:00:17.355 --> 00:00:24.090
that is to say after 420 is

00:00:24.090 --> 00:00:28.965
because of the historian Bede

00:00:28.965 --> 00:00:33.015
writing in the early
eighth century,

00:00:33.015 --> 00:00:37.150
a monk at Jarrow

00:00:37.150 --> 00:00:42.605
which was a part of
a twin monastery in Northumbria.

00:00:42.605 --> 00:00:46.400
You can see on your map
the Northeastern

00:00:46.400 --> 00:00:51.180
part of England before you
get to what's now Scotland.

00:00:51.560 --> 00:00:54.470
Bede wrote among other things

00:00:54.470 --> 00:00:56.600
a history of the English
church and people,

00:00:56.600 --> 00:01:00.295
which is full of miracles

00:01:00.295 --> 00:01:05.210
and very pro Christian as
much as Gregory of Tour,

00:01:05.210 --> 00:01:09.410
but is a much more easy

00:01:09.410 --> 00:01:11.150
to follow narrative and

00:01:11.150 --> 00:01:13.490
a narrative with
a certain kind of point.

00:01:13.490 --> 00:01:15.230
It's about the
conversion of England

00:01:15.230 --> 00:01:17.630
and the establishment
of the church.

00:01:17.630 --> 00:01:20.710
The other advantage for
England over Ireland in

00:01:20.710 --> 00:01:23.665
terms of evidence is archaeology.

00:01:23.665 --> 00:01:25.600
A lot more has been done with

00:01:25.600 --> 00:01:30.370
excavating sites in England,

00:01:30.370 --> 00:01:33.820
and by England we mean
literally England,

00:01:33.820 --> 00:01:35.605
the part that is not Wales,

00:01:35.605 --> 00:01:38.210
not Scotland, not Ireland,

00:01:38.210 --> 00:01:41.395
the part of the British
Isles, the ensemble.

00:01:41.395 --> 00:01:44.035
Essentially the two islands

00:01:44.035 --> 00:01:46.450
are referred to as
the British Isles.

00:01:46.450 --> 00:01:49.680
Britain is England, Scotland,

00:01:49.680 --> 00:01:52.455
and Wales, Ireland is Ireland.

00:01:52.455 --> 00:01:56.505
The Britons however,
B-R-I-T-O-N-S,

00:01:56.505 --> 00:02:00.610
are the collective term
for the Celtic population.

00:02:00.610 --> 00:02:04.055
Celtic is both a linguistic group

00:02:04.055 --> 00:02:07.625
and a somewhat vague ethnic term.

00:02:07.625 --> 00:02:10.085
It means the people
who were there

00:02:10.085 --> 00:02:13.970
in the British Isles
before the Romans came,

00:02:13.970 --> 00:02:17.570
and who were there afterwards

00:02:17.570 --> 00:02:22.550
fighting invaders from Europe.

00:02:22.550 --> 00:02:24.950
These invaders who come in the

00:02:24.950 --> 00:02:28.025
440 is known as the Anglo-Saxons.

00:02:28.025 --> 00:02:31.700
Bede tells us it's
the Anglo at the Saxons,

00:02:31.700 --> 00:02:33.485
excuse me, the Angles,

00:02:33.485 --> 00:02:36.190
the Saxons and the Jews.

00:02:36.190 --> 00:02:39.734
The Angles give
their name to England,

00:02:39.734 --> 00:02:44.265
Angle land, the Jews
we know nothing about.

00:02:44.265 --> 00:02:47.100
So a certain kind of

00:02:47.100 --> 00:02:51.965
medievalist will go on
about funding a journal of

00:02:51.965 --> 00:02:54.650
jute studies and inviting

00:02:54.650 --> 00:02:56.855
contributors to something
that we really have

00:02:56.855 --> 00:02:59.540
absolutely no idea of it
being in that league of

00:02:59.540 --> 00:03:02.510
smallest thinnest bond
[inaudible]

00:03:02.510 --> 00:03:05.450
at least in terms of
three-dimensional books.

00:03:05.450 --> 00:03:08.660
The Saxons come from there

00:03:08.660 --> 00:03:12.050
is still a very large part
of Germany called Saxony.

00:03:12.050 --> 00:03:14.690
What the nature of
these peoples are,

00:03:14.690 --> 00:03:16.280
how they were
differentiated among

00:03:16.280 --> 00:03:19.940
themselves is
a source of a lot of

00:03:19.940 --> 00:03:22.760
real or at least it looks

00:03:22.760 --> 00:03:26.090
real scholarship as opposed
to studying the Jews,

00:03:26.090 --> 00:03:27.845
but we don't have
to go into that.

00:03:27.845 --> 00:03:30.020
But you need to get
the cast of characters.

00:03:30.020 --> 00:03:36.155
Celts, Anglo-Saxons,
the Anglo-Saxons

00:03:36.155 --> 00:03:39.650
conquer much of
the island more or

00:03:39.650 --> 00:03:43.235
less what would become
England but not all.

00:03:43.235 --> 00:03:45.380
They do not conquer Scotland,

00:03:45.380 --> 00:03:47.585
they do not conquer Wales,

00:03:47.585 --> 00:03:49.625
and they don't really
conquer Cornwall.

00:03:49.625 --> 00:03:53.960
So the Western part of
Britain remains Celtic

00:03:53.960 --> 00:03:56.540
and to this day Wales and

00:03:56.540 --> 00:03:59.490
Scotland considered themselves
different from England.

00:03:59.490 --> 00:04:02.735
You can get into a lot
of trouble by calling

00:04:02.735 --> 00:04:06.500
that area England
with the people there

00:04:06.500 --> 00:04:09.920
and particularly in
Scotland there's

00:04:09.920 --> 00:04:11.735
a possibility that
they may separate

00:04:11.735 --> 00:04:15.035
from the United Kingdom
at some point.

00:04:15.035 --> 00:04:19.655
Ireland, Ireland was never
occupied by the Romans.

00:04:19.655 --> 00:04:23.600
Ireland was chaotic,

00:04:23.600 --> 00:04:26.960
was in contact with
the Roman Empire,

00:04:26.960 --> 00:04:30.025
but was not part of it.

00:04:30.025 --> 00:04:32.930
This makes some
difference and we'll

00:04:32.930 --> 00:04:35.510
talk about it when we come
to talk about conversion,

00:04:35.510 --> 00:04:37.700
but it doesn't make
as much difference as it sounds

00:04:37.700 --> 00:04:40.265
because the thing
about England or

00:04:40.265 --> 00:04:43.415
Britain is that the Roman impress

00:04:43.415 --> 00:04:47.585
there would be almost wiped
out once the Romans withdrew.

00:04:47.585 --> 00:04:50.660
So in contrast to what we saw

00:04:50.660 --> 00:04:53.540
with Gregory of Tour
and Merovingian Gaul,

00:04:53.540 --> 00:04:57.709
Merovingian Frankish kingdom,

00:04:57.709 --> 00:05:03.410
the Roman influence in
Britain is almost wiped out.

00:05:03.410 --> 00:05:08.720
Recall what we saw as
persistence of Roman practices

00:05:08.720 --> 00:05:14.959
in the Merovingian kingdom,
bishops, cities,

00:05:14.959 --> 00:05:25.280
the Latin language, tax
records, written legal codes,

00:05:25.280 --> 00:05:27.080
that is not to say that the

00:05:27.080 --> 00:05:28.700
Merovingians weren't as I said

00:05:28.700 --> 00:05:34.015
before to be described by
technical terms like thugs,

00:05:34.015 --> 00:05:39.480
or that this was a sleek
well-functioning Kingdom,

00:05:39.480 --> 00:05:41.360
you landed at the airport

00:05:41.360 --> 00:05:44.660
and got the train immediately
and everything was

00:05:44.660 --> 00:05:47.330
sleek and nice like Amsterdam or

00:05:47.330 --> 00:05:50.630
someplace like that as
opposed to Kennedy.

00:05:50.630 --> 00:05:56.605
But that the Roman inheritance

00:05:56.605 --> 00:05:59.880
was visible and influential.

00:05:59.880 --> 00:06:03.470
In Britain when
the Roman troops withdrew to

00:06:03.470 --> 00:06:10.025
fight the invaders in Gaul,

00:06:10.025 --> 00:06:13.630
this ended Roman
society in Britain.

00:06:13.630 --> 00:06:14.660
The reason for this is

00:06:14.660 --> 00:06:16.370
partly that Britain
was a frontier,

00:06:16.370 --> 00:06:17.630
viewed from the point of view of

00:06:17.630 --> 00:06:19.220
the Mediterranean the center

00:06:19.220 --> 00:06:21.840
of gravity of the Roman Empire.

00:06:22.120 --> 00:06:28.960
The frontier symbolized most

00:06:28.960 --> 00:06:31.010
dramatically by walls the

00:06:31.010 --> 00:06:33.570
most famous of which
is Hadrian's Wall,

00:06:33.570 --> 00:06:37.250
a wall that separated
out the Barbarians.

00:06:37.250 --> 00:06:39.050
But since you didn't have a river

00:06:39.050 --> 00:06:41.090
like the Danube or the Rhine,

00:06:41.090 --> 00:06:43.640
there seemed to be
no natural frontier.

00:06:43.640 --> 00:06:46.055
Remnants of Hadrian's Wall are

00:06:46.055 --> 00:06:53.080
the largest souvenir
of the Roman era,

00:06:53.080 --> 00:06:55.580
a wall to keep out
the Barbarians from the North

00:06:55.580 --> 00:06:56.690
because in fact the Romans didn't

00:06:56.690 --> 00:06:58.385
conquer the entire island.

00:06:58.385 --> 00:07:00.810
They conquered the parts they
thought were worthwhile,

00:07:00.810 --> 00:07:02.835
and they did think
it was worthwhile.

00:07:02.835 --> 00:07:07.010
Frontier or not, we know that
the Romans built villas,

00:07:07.010 --> 00:07:08.959
might be a little cold

00:07:08.959 --> 00:07:12.020
the somewhat open-air
Mediterranean plan things,

00:07:12.020 --> 00:07:17.330
but Mosaic courtyards,
drank a lot of wine,

00:07:17.330 --> 00:07:21.729
much of it imported,
built cities,

00:07:21.729 --> 00:07:27.395
walls, other fortifications,
cultivated land.

00:07:27.395 --> 00:07:32.030
So it's not as if there wasn't
a serious Roman province

00:07:32.030 --> 00:07:36.530
of Britain from its conquest
in the late first century,

00:07:36.530 --> 00:07:40.715
until its abandonment in
the early fifth century.

00:07:40.715 --> 00:07:45.230
But here the invaders
tended to obliterate

00:07:45.230 --> 00:07:49.719
much of what had been
there in Roman times,

00:07:49.719 --> 00:07:52.610
and the Celtic population who had

00:07:52.610 --> 00:07:55.400
been Romanized at least
at the elite levels,

00:07:55.400 --> 00:07:57.755
the Celtic population didn't

00:07:57.755 --> 00:08:01.850
really save very much
from the Roman Empire.

00:08:01.850 --> 00:08:04.250
The Celts might remain

00:08:04.250 --> 00:08:08.160
Christian whereas
the invaders were Pagan.

00:08:10.670 --> 00:08:13.665
But the Celts tended not to have

00:08:13.665 --> 00:08:17.200
cities or at least large centers,

00:08:17.450 --> 00:08:20.820
and they tended not to have or

00:08:20.820 --> 00:08:23.745
retain Roman forms of government.

00:08:23.745 --> 00:08:25.785
The one kind of,

00:08:25.785 --> 00:08:28.200
if not literally interesting

00:08:28.200 --> 00:08:30.360
at least weird aspect of

00:08:30.360 --> 00:08:33.990
Celtic Roman Resistance is
the figure of King Arthur.

00:08:33.990 --> 00:08:35.655
I'm going to bring him up now

00:08:35.655 --> 00:08:37.230
and then I'm going to drop him.

00:08:37.230 --> 00:08:40.050
King Arthur belongs properly to

00:08:40.050 --> 00:08:42.780
the continuation of
this course because

00:08:42.780 --> 00:08:48.700
his legendary status starts

00:08:48.860 --> 00:08:51.690
really in the world of romance,

00:08:51.690 --> 00:08:53.460
of French romance and then of

00:08:53.460 --> 00:08:56.550
international romance
chivalric literature.

00:08:56.550 --> 00:08:58.890
By romance we mean, not only

00:08:58.890 --> 00:09:01.365
love stories but
novels of chivalry,

00:09:01.365 --> 00:09:04.020
of knights, of battles.

00:09:04.020 --> 00:09:10.365
He is a figure who is
99.9 percent legend.

00:09:10.365 --> 00:09:15.000
Whatever the remainder of
that 0.1 percent real.

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:16.320
So far as he's real,

00:09:16.320 --> 00:09:18.255
he may be identified with

00:09:18.255 --> 00:09:21.390
Celtic resistance to
the Anglo-Saxon invaders,

00:09:21.390 --> 00:09:24.060
Celtic Roman resistance in

00:09:24.060 --> 00:09:27.550
the late fifth, early
sixth centuries.

00:09:27.980 --> 00:09:34.695
But the proportion of art
to history in this is,

00:09:34.695 --> 00:09:38.895
if not 99.9 at least
very, very substantial.

00:09:38.895 --> 00:09:43.800
The original setting of
the Arthurian stories

00:09:43.800 --> 00:09:48.330
is that of the resistance to
the Anglo-Saxon invaders.

00:09:48.330 --> 00:09:52.200
The Arthurian romances do

00:09:52.200 --> 00:09:55.470
have a Celtic beginning,
well not a kind of,

00:09:55.470 --> 00:09:57.015
they have a Celtic beginning,

00:09:57.015 --> 00:09:59.385
and then they are
appropriated by people

00:09:59.385 --> 00:10:02.160
in the Romance
language tradition,

00:10:02.160 --> 00:10:04.870
French, first of all.

00:10:06.590 --> 00:10:10.499
So as Walkom says on page 151,

00:10:10.499 --> 00:10:14.130
nowhere else in the Roman Empire

00:10:14.130 --> 00:10:15.975
was the collapse of culture,

00:10:15.975 --> 00:10:19.080
economy and urbanization
so complete.

00:10:19.080 --> 00:10:21.135
He uses that wonderful phrase

00:10:21.135 --> 00:10:26.575
again, radical economic
simplification,

00:10:26.575 --> 00:10:31.020
ie, there's no more plumbing,

00:10:31.020 --> 00:10:34.350
there's no more of what we would

00:10:34.350 --> 00:10:37.860
consider to be
affluent civilized society.

00:10:37.860 --> 00:10:40.605
The ceramics don't come
from Africa anymore,

00:10:40.605 --> 00:10:43.155
the wine doesn't come
from France anymore,

00:10:43.155 --> 00:10:46.455
people are reduced to

00:10:46.455 --> 00:10:48.120
a kind of subsistence or

00:10:48.120 --> 00:10:50.130
at least most people
because as we'll see,

00:10:50.130 --> 00:10:52.170
some of these kings
actually are able to

00:10:52.170 --> 00:10:56.470
get some luxury goods
from abroad.

00:10:57.350 --> 00:11:01.200
If it were just a story
of barbarisation,

00:11:01.200 --> 00:11:02.745
it would be less
interesting then.

00:11:02.745 --> 00:11:07.770
In fact, the peculiar nature
of England in this period,

00:11:07.770 --> 00:11:11.850
which goes from being
a contested territory

00:11:11.850 --> 00:11:16.650
between the Germanic invaders
and the Celtic population,

00:11:16.650 --> 00:11:20.640
to a kingdoms slowly converted in

00:11:20.640 --> 00:11:22.200
the course of the seventh century

00:11:22.200 --> 00:11:24.930
to Christianity from paganism,

00:11:24.930 --> 00:11:29.970
to the leading center
of culture in Europe.

00:11:29.970 --> 00:11:35.220
Bede, who lived from 673-735 was

00:11:35.220 --> 00:11:37.260
the most cultivated scholar in

00:11:37.260 --> 00:11:41.130
Europe of the early
eighth century.

00:11:41.130 --> 00:11:43.440
The most cultivated
scholar in Europe of

00:11:43.440 --> 00:11:48.990
the late eighth century
was also from England,

00:11:48.990 --> 00:11:54.880
Alcuin, counselor and
adviser to Charlemagne.

00:11:55.370 --> 00:11:58.080
How do you go from being

00:11:58.080 --> 00:12:08.025
a barbarian enough area

00:12:08.025 --> 00:12:10.950
to having the largest libraries,

00:12:10.950 --> 00:12:15.210
the most cultivated scholars?

00:12:15.210 --> 00:12:17.910
Now, it is true as I
think I've said before

00:12:17.910 --> 00:12:21.240
that any time you can say

00:12:21.240 --> 00:12:24.405
that such and such a person
was the smartest person

00:12:24.405 --> 00:12:28.335
in Europe has got to
be a fairly bad time.

00:12:28.335 --> 00:12:30.210
In the 19th century,

00:12:30.210 --> 00:12:33.345
you have your choice from
all sorts of scientific,

00:12:33.345 --> 00:12:36.840
literary, other kinds of

00:12:36.840 --> 00:12:41.295
intellectual experts who
would even dare to say.

00:12:41.295 --> 00:12:46.580
But we know that Boethius
and Cassiodorus are

00:12:46.580 --> 00:12:48.380
the smartest guys in Europe in

00:12:48.380 --> 00:12:50.150
the sixth century
because they have

00:12:50.150 --> 00:12:52.430
access to stuff that
almost no one else does,

00:12:52.430 --> 00:12:54.200
because their writing about

00:12:54.200 --> 00:12:56.180
classical authors
that almost no one

00:12:56.180 --> 00:12:58.570
else has in their libraries.

00:12:58.570 --> 00:13:01.500
We know that Isidore
of Seville is probably

00:13:01.500 --> 00:13:02.790
the smartest guy of

00:13:02.790 --> 00:13:06.300
the early seventh century,
and Visigothic Spain.

00:13:06.300 --> 00:13:08.355
Because we have his works,

00:13:08.355 --> 00:13:10.260
we have an idea of
what he's read,

00:13:10.260 --> 00:13:11.805
we know his sources

00:13:11.805 --> 00:13:14.970
and again he's got
the biggest library.

00:13:14.970 --> 00:13:19.320
Biggest library may
mean 100 books,

00:13:19.320 --> 00:13:21.825
but 100 books in 700 AD

00:13:21.825 --> 00:13:24.135
is a serious collection
of knowledge.

00:13:24.135 --> 00:13:26.715
Now, this is not easy knowledge,

00:13:26.715 --> 00:13:30.850
this is not as if everything were

00:13:38.290 --> 00:13:42.005
like Wikipedia five years ago,

00:13:42.005 --> 00:13:44.975
elementary and often wrong,

00:13:44.975 --> 00:13:48.510
these are very different kinds

00:13:48.510 --> 00:13:50.715
of works from what
might interest us.

00:13:50.715 --> 00:13:52.770
Certainly a lot of
biblical stuff,

00:13:52.770 --> 00:13:56.535
but also for example a lot
of computing of time.

00:13:56.535 --> 00:13:59.220
Bede would be remembered

00:13:59.220 --> 00:14:01.395
for the history of
the English church and people,

00:14:01.395 --> 00:14:07.320
but also for a lot of his
works on figuring out time.

00:14:07.320 --> 00:14:10.740
He is credited, although
not uniquely credited,

00:14:10.740 --> 00:14:13.125
but as an important person
in the development

00:14:13.125 --> 00:14:16.440
of the BC, AD scheme.

00:14:16.440 --> 00:14:18.990
Believe it or not people
are not born into

00:14:18.990 --> 00:14:22.665
the world calculating
according to BC, AD,

00:14:22.665 --> 00:14:25.305
lots of people calculate
according to other systems,

00:14:25.305 --> 00:14:26.895
how did they come up with this,

00:14:26.895 --> 00:14:31.770
and moreover how do they then
fit the calendar into it?

00:14:31.770 --> 00:14:34.560
How do you keep
time when you don't

00:14:34.560 --> 00:14:38.385
have electric or battery
operated clocks?

00:14:38.385 --> 00:14:42.430
How do you know what
the seasonal changes are?

00:14:42.950 --> 00:14:46.545
But in fact the most
troublesome problem

00:14:46.545 --> 00:14:48.510
which had been particularly

00:14:48.510 --> 00:14:50.940
controversial to the conversion

00:14:50.940 --> 00:14:54.225
of England in the
generation before Bede,

00:14:54.225 --> 00:14:57.810
in the early seventh
and mid seventh century

00:14:57.810 --> 00:15:00.315
was the calculation of Easter.

00:15:00.315 --> 00:15:03.030
Easter is a real problem.

00:15:03.030 --> 00:15:04.650
Now, naturally it's not

00:15:04.650 --> 00:15:07.095
a problem if someone
else tells you.

00:15:07.095 --> 00:15:10.380
If in 1970 you open up

00:15:10.380 --> 00:15:14.595
a little pocket book
calendar and it says,

00:15:14.595 --> 00:15:16.755
okay, Easter is this day,

00:15:16.755 --> 00:15:20.070
you trust them, or now,

00:15:20.070 --> 00:15:22.080
if you have some feature on

00:15:22.080 --> 00:15:24.930
your iPhone that gives

00:15:24.930 --> 00:15:27.360
you Easter for the
next 3,000 years,

00:15:27.360 --> 00:15:30.600
in case you want to
know when Easter is in

00:15:30.600 --> 00:15:36.180
3500 AD, no problem.

00:15:36.180 --> 00:15:37.800
But if you're out there in

00:15:37.800 --> 00:15:40.980
Northumbria or anywhere
for that matter,

00:15:40.980 --> 00:15:42.660
in a monastery somewhere,

00:15:42.660 --> 00:15:44.370
where it's really crucial

00:15:44.370 --> 00:15:46.380
to celebrate it on the right day.

